    "summary": "The Decline of the Maurya Empire (232–185 BC) followed the death of [[event:1098|Ashoka the Great]] and saw the progressive fragmentation of the subcontinent's first pan-Indian state, culminating in the assassination of the last Mauryan emperor and the rise of successor kingdoms.\n\nAshoka's successors lacked his administrative genius and moral authority. The empire proved too vast to govern effectively without strong central leadership, and regional governors — many of them Mauryan princes — increasingly acted as independent rulers. Repeated division of the empire among heirs compounded the problem. Military weakness became apparent as Greek kingdoms in the northwest and local powers across the Deccan reasserted independence. The last Mauryan emperor, Brihadratha, was assassinated by his own general Pushyamitra Shunga in 185 BC, who then founded the [[event:1103|Shunga Dynasty]] that replaced Mauryan rule in the Gangetic plain.",
